                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="12848388" author="tlipcon" created="Mon, 22 Mar 2010 22:09:05 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;the &quot;throw up our hands and exit, no bandaids&quot; is also very useful in testing, where we care more about figuring out the root causes of the issues. In production we&apos;d probably rather keep the cluster up than find the root cause.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12848390" author="stack" created="Mon, 22 Mar 2010 22:15:05 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;For an instance of a location where such a configuration would be useful, see &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-2358&quot; title=&quot;Store doReconstructionLog will fail if oldlogfile.log is empty and won&amp;#39;t load region&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;HBASE-2358&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;HBASE-2358&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; and the comments post-issue-close.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12848392" author="tlipcon" created="Mon, 22 Mar 2010 22:17:26 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Another example is in HLog where we swallow exceptions writing the split logs. Before fixing &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-2355&quot; title=&quot;unsychronized logWriters map is mutated from several threads in HLog splitting&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;HBASE-2355&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;HBASE-2355&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; I was seeing a case where exceptions closing the output of log splitting were ignored and then data was silently lost (even with sync). I would rather have had the HMaster shut itself down.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12848599" author="apurtell" created="Tue, 23 Mar 2010 07:41:26 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This is related to &quot;ride over restart&quot;: &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-2183&quot; title=&quot;Ride over restart&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;HBASE-2183&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;HBASE-2183&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, which could be better named perhaps. The umbrella is for issues dealing with temporary unavailability. Temporary unavailability of the filesystem is one subset of conditions where now HBase will shut down to prevent data loss, but, in our case, we want to stay up, switching temporarily to read-only and serving data in a degraded mode (with flag set in responses from the cluster to indicate such). &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13487403" author="tlipcon" created="Wed, 31 Oct 2012 00:27:50 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;this has been somewhat addressed by hbase.skip.errors and hbase.hlog.split.skip.errors, implemented elsewhere&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
